Week 6 - Bimodal Networks¶

Betsy Rosalen and Mikhail Groysman¶

Project Overview¶

Here is a dataset that shows a simple 2-node network: the attendance of 18 Southern Women at 14 social events:

  1. Brief Description. Small musty datasets like that from this 1941 study have proven very valuable in testing and comparing new network algorithms.
  2. Dataset.
  3. Python code to create dataset: https://networkx.github.io/documentation/stable/auto_examples/algorithms/plot_davis_club.html

What can you infer about the relationships between (1) the women, and (2) the social events?

Davis Southern Club Women¶

DESCRIPTION One 1814 matrix, binary.

BACKGROUND These data were collected by Davis et al in the 1930s. They represent observed attendance at 14 social events by 18 Southern women. The result is a person-by-event matrix: cell (i,j) is 1 if person i attended social event j, and 0 otherwise.

REFERENCES

  • Breiger R. (1974). The duality of persons and groups. Social Forces, 53, 181-190.
  • Davis, A et al. (1941). Deep South. Chicago: University of Chicago Press.

Women Degrees¶

In [117]:
# project bipartite graph onto women nodes
W = bipartite.projected_graph(G, women)
print('')
print("# of Friends, Member")

W_degrees = {}
for w in women:
    W_degrees[w] = W.degree(w)

for w in sorted(W_degrees, key=W_degrees.get, reverse=True):
  print(W_degrees[w], w)

Women Weights¶

In [118]:
# project bipartite graph onto women nodes keeping number of co-occurence
# the degree computed is weighted and counts the total number of shared contacts
W = bipartite.weighted_projected_graph(G, women)
print('')
print("#Friend meetings, Member")
    
W_weights = {}
for w in women:
    W_weights[w] = W.degree(w, weight='weight')

for w in sorted(W_weights, key=W_weights.get, reverse=True):
    print(W_weights[w], w)

#Friend meetings, Member

We can see a big difference betwwen the strength of connections when we evaluate simply the degrees vs the weights. Looking onnly at degrees it seems as if almost all the women are almost equally connected with only 3 women (Olivia Carleton, Flora Price, Charlotte McDowd) who have considerably less connections than the rest.

However when we look at the weighted connections, we can see that there are two women (Theresa Anderson and Evelyn Jefferson) who have considerably more influence than the rest and a more varying range of influence from top to bottom. Olivia Carleton and Flora Price are still considerably less influential, but Charlotte McDowd has more influence in her relationships despite the lower number of connections.

The Circular layout shows two clear zones of influence or 'cliques'. One centered around the top right corner near Evelyn, Laura, Theresa and Brenda and the other around the bottom left near Katherina, Sylvia and Nora. While the Spring layout graph above clearly showed who were the most influential people, the two separate cliques were not readily apparent in that layout.

Bimodal Graphs¶

draw_spring layout¶

In [127]:
colors = []
for node, data in G.nodes(data=True):
    if data['bipartite'] == 1:
        colors.append('cornflowerblue')         
    else:
        colors.append('orchid')

nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_size=1000, node_color=colors, font_size=12, font_family="calibri", 
                 width=weights, edge_color="darkgray", alpha=0.8)

draw_circular layout¶

In [128]:
nx.draw_circular(G, with_labels=True, node_size=1000, node_color=colors, font_size=12, font_family="calibri", 
                 width=weights, edge_color="darkgray", alpha=0.8)

The _drawcircular layout is definitely a much better layout for this particular network. Relationships are much clearer in both the individual node network graphs and the bimodal network graph.

Final Conclusions:¶

Women:

  • Theresa Anderson is by far the most active and influential participant in club life
  • Evelyn Jefferson, Brenda Rodgers, Sylvia Avondale, Laura Mandeville, and Nora Fayette are also very influential but not necessarily in all the same clubs.
  • Flora Rice and Olivia Carlenton are pretty isolated from club life
  • There is another cluster, Nora Fayere, Sylvia Avondale, and Katherina Rogers, who are pretty active in many simular clubs.

Clubs:

  • Clubs E6, E7, E8, and E9 are the most popular.
  • Clubs E1, E13, and E14 are the least popular clubs.

The 4 most active women and 4 most popular clubs:

  • Theresa Anderson attends all four of the most influential clubs: E6, E7, E8 and E9
  • Evelyn Jefferson attends E6, E8 and E9 clubs, but not E7
  • Brenda Rodgers attends E6, E7 and E8 clubs, but not E9
  • Sylvia Avondale attends E7, E8, and E9 clubs, but not E6

Complete Graphs?¶

In [129]:
complete = bipartite.complete_bipartite_graph(W, C)
nx.draw(complete, with_labels=True, node_size=1000, node_color=colors, font_size=12, font_family="calibri", 
                 width=np.log(weights)**2, edge_color="darkgray", alpha=0.8)
In [130]:
complete = bipartite.complete_bipartite_graph(W, C)
nx.draw_circular(complete, with_labels=True, node_size=1000, node_color=colors, font_size=12, font_family="calibri", 
                 width=np.log(weights)**2, edge_color="darkgray", alpha=0.8)

The bipartite.complete_bipartite_graph function shows a lot more connections than the default NetworkX graph, but it's not immediately clear what the differece is or what are the differences in calculations, so it's hard to say what we are looking at here. We'd like to do more reasearch and reading into the difference between these two functions before reaching any conclusions about them.
